<DOC><DOCNO>  ZF108-276-802  </DOCNO><DOCID>08 276 802.andO;</DOCID><JOURNAL>Computer Weekly  March 15 1990 n1205 p71(1).andM;</JOURNAL><TITLE>UNIX and MS-DOS: a split decision?andO;</TITLE><AUTHOR>Banks, Martin.andM;</AUTHOR><TEXT><ABSTRACT>The growing popularity of UNIX may result in considerable changesfor MS-DOS users.andP;  MS-DOS is less complicated than UNIX, andaverage MS-DOS users are likely to find UNIX installationdifficult, time consuming, and prone to errors.andP;  Users who want toinstall a UNIX partition while maintaining DOS capabilities willbe faced with an even more complex process.andP;  DOS usersimplementing UNIX will gain multitasking capabilities, and thisinvolves adding additional tools to make these environmentstransparent.andP;  MS-DOS remains popular, and is likely to survive forsome time.andP;  This is because many tools are available to mix andmatch it with Unix, and because users want to protect theirinvestments in data, applications, and user training andexperience.andM;</ABSTRACT></TEXT><DESCRIPT>Topic:     UNIXMS-DOSTrendsEnd UsersUser Behavior.andM;</DESCRIPT></DOC>